## Action items

- [x] Inspect the RISC-V trap entry assembly in
  `arch/riscv/kernel/entry.S`. The `tp`/`CSR_SCRATCH` contract
  is sound:
  - `head.S:198` initialises `mscratch=0` in M-mode at boot.
  - `handle_exception:102` does `csrrw tp, CSR_SCRATCH, tp` —
    swap user-tp ↔ kernel-tp at trap entry. `bnez tp` discriminates
    came-from-user (tp != 0) vs came-from-kernel (tp = 0 since
    scratch held 0 in kernel mode).
  - `handle_exception:166` clears `mscratch=0` after the swap-
    plus-save so a recursive in-kernel exception sees the zero
    sentinel.
  - `ret_from_exception:239` writes `mscratch=tp` before mret
    when returning to U-mode, ensuring the next U→M trap can
    swap correctly.
  So the kernel's contract is correct given that mstatus.MPP and
  CSR_SCRATCH are preserved across our SoC's mret/trap. The MPP
  fix `aab129b` covered MPP. CSR_SCRATCH is a regular machine-
  level CSR we expose through `Riski5.CSR.csrMscratch` — should
  also work, but worth verifying our pipeline doesn't drop
  scratch writes mid-trap-entry.
- [ ] Verify `mscratch` reads/writes round-trip correctly through
  our trap-entry pipeline. Likely instrumentation: emit
  `mscratch` in the boot-stub's TRAP-INFO dump (it's already in
  there per `LinuxBootMaster.hs:178-180`), then trigger a
  controlled U→M trap and read the byte stream.
- [ ] Trace the init-thread PC explicitly (= the PC where the
  kernel runs `rest_init` / `kernel_init` / `kernel_init_freeable`)
  vs the IRQ-handler PCs we already see. If the init thread's
  PC is *also* stuck on a single instruction, that's the actual
  hang site. Currently we only see the IRQ-handler clusters.
- [ ] If the above doesn't pinpoint, isolate by toggling
  `CONFIG_STACKPROTECTOR_PER_TASK` independently of
  `STACKPROTECTOR_STRONG` to check whether the per-task tp-
  based canary access is the discriminator. (User direction
  is to keep all three on; do this only as a temporary diagnostic
  swap, revert immediately after.)

